Visualizations for both sets look the same aside from the test data not having the including the transport status. A few things to highlight:

  • A little over half of the passengers are from planet Earth

  • Passengers between the ages of 20-24 have the higest count
  • Most of the passengers are between the ages of 15-39

If a passenger is spending x amount of money at the food court on their trip, they are inclined to spend money in general. Thus, them spending money at the VR Deck or the Spa is plausible.

Since almost all of the passengers are not VIP, we will remove the column. The only inidication of wealth status can be found in the bill totals of the passengers. We will also remove the name, passenger ID and cabin number since they all hold completely unqiue values that do not necessarily give us any relevant insight since we are looking at the passengers as a group, not individuals.

Part 3: Algorithms¶

We will be needing a confusion matrix for each algorithm so we will define a function now for it and call it when needed

In [230]:
def print_conf_matrix(title, conf_matrix):
    

    group_names = ['True Neg','False Pos','False Neg','True Pos']
    group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}".format(value) for value in
                    conf_matrix.flatten()]
    group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in
                         conf_matrix.flatten()/np.sum(conf_matrix)]
    labels = [f"{v1}\n{v2}\n{v3}" for v1, v2, v3 in
              zip(group_names,group_counts,group_percentages)]
    labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2,2)

    ax = sns.heatmap(conf_matrix, annot=labels, fmt='', cmap='Greens')
    #ax.set_title('Confusion Matrix for Logistic Regression\n\n');
    ax.set_title(title);
    ax.set_xlabel('\nPredicted Values')
    ax.set_ylabel('Actual Values ');
    ax.xaxis.set_ticklabels(['False','True'])
    ax.yaxis.set_ticklabels(['False','True'])
    plt.show()

                conf_matrix.flatten()]
group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in
                     conf_matrix.flatten()/np.sum(conf_matrix)]
labels = [f"{v1}\n{v2}\n{v3}" for v1, v2, v3 in
          zip(group_names,group_counts,group_percentages)]
labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2,2)

TN = conf_matrix[0,0]
FN = conf_matrix[1,0]
TP = conf_matrix[1,1]
FP = conf_matrix[0,1]
TPR = (TP/(TP+FN)) * 100
TNR = (TN/(FP+TN)) * 100 

print("Percent of passengers transported to another dimension correctly predicted: {0:.2f}%\n".format(round(TPR, 2)))
print("Percent of passengers not transported to another dimension: {0:.2f}%\n".format(round(TNR, 2)))

Further Exploration of Random Forest - Anna¶

Since the Random Forest Classifier had the highest accuracy, we will explore it further to see how we can improve upon it and make it as accurate as possible in future work

Recall/Precison Analysis:

In [252]:
scores = random_forest.predict_proba(X_train)
scores = scores[:,1]

precision, recall, threshold = precision_recall_curve(y_train, scores)
def plot_precision_and_recall(precision, recall, threshold):
    plt.plot(threshold, precision[:-1], "r-", label="precision", linewidth=5)
    plt.plot(threshold, recall[:-1], "b", label="recall", linewidth=5)
    plt.xlabel("threshold", fontsize=19)
    plt.legend(loc="upper right", fontsize=19)
    plt.ylim([0, 1])

plt.figure(figsize=(14, 7))
plot_precision_and_recall(precision, recall, threshold)
plt.show()

We will also look at the ROC AUC curve to see the trade off between the true positive rate (TPR) and false positive rate (FPR).

In [253]:
FPR, TPR, thresholds = roc_curve(y_train, scores)

def plot_roc_curve(FPR, TPR, label=None):
    plt.plot(FPR, TPR, linewidth=2, label=label)
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'r', linewidth=4)
    plt.axis([0, 1, 0, 1])
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate (FPR)', fontsize=16)
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate (TPR)', fontsize=16)

plt.figure(figsize=(14, 7))
plot_roc_curve(FPR, TPR)
plt.show()
roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_train, scores)
print("ROC-AUC-Score: {0:.2f}%\n".format(round(roc_auc * 100, 2)))

ROC-AUC-Score: 98.23%

We can see the classifier (red line) is very far away from the curve which is ideal. We can confirm this by looking at the ROC-AUC score and see that it is 98%.
